snippet.title: (Wes Anderson) What Do You Do?
snippet.description:
Best Quality - 1080p
Headphones Recommended


Wes Anderson is probably my favorite director of all time. Every work of his is both hilarious, and deeply saddening, while also extremely childish and heartwarming. I think that "childish" theme plays a big factor since his films are undeniably adult-content, with a colorful cascade that differentiates itself to every film, making every work different, yet the same. His awkward and hilariously abrupt humor is probably my favorite feature of these. It's very real and EXTREMELY natural when it's presented. The dialogue obviously plays a big part in that, which leads me onto the fact that his use of dialogue is the best i've seen in film. Nothing is unnatural and it's very messy, but in a good way. Messy as in it's something you would say in your daily life, and almost as if there is no script. Grammar is used incorrectly from a child showing almost a struggle to communicate correctly, but perfectly saying what he wants to say through means of leaving behind a filter of correctness and structure. We are left with an emotion after these films end. That of which I can't really pinpoint. I'm better at this when I'm saying it out loud, typing sucks.

snippet.title: (Fargo) Conflict and Misunderstanding
snippet.description:
WOW ok season 2 of Fargo ended last night and I must say I loved the 2nd season. I actually enjoyed it more than the first. There is so much that goes on in the season and the characters are VERY well thought out. To be honest though, I wouldn't have actually enjoyed the 2nd season more if it wasn't for the acting. The acting is actually what makes the season in my opinion.

The ending was fantastic! I had some small problems with it like the fate of Hanzee, and the finale was slightly dragged out, but if it wasn't for the final scene with the Solverson's, I wouldn't have enjoyed it as much as I did. It really leaves off on a positive, unexpected note. I ACTUALLY DID NOT KNOW THE EPISODE WAS GOING TO END THERE lol. It was very well done, I looked into Ted Danson's monologue at the end and found out how it sort of explains the entire season. It shows how almost all of the conflicts that occurred in the series were from miscommunication and misunderstanding. Look it up it's crazy. Noah Hawley did it again:D
